The XO-3b data used for the Data Challenge consisted of 10 individual secondary eclipse measurements originally analyzed by \citet{2014ApJ...794..134W}, and summarized in Table 1.  All measurements were made with post-cryogenic {\hbox{\sl Spitzer\/}}\ in 2012 and 2013, and were taken as part of Program ID (PID) 90032.  The first 6 epochs took place within about 30 days of each other; the last 4 occurred about 1/2 year later and also spanned 30 days.  Each epoch consisted of two Astronomical Observation Requests (AORs): an 11-exposure, 30 minute ``Pre'' AOR to allow short term pointing drift to settle; and a 233-exposure, 8.5 hour ``Main'' AOR that contained the secondary eclipse.  Each exposure produced a FITS format image file, containing a cube of 64 32$\times$32 pixel images taken 2s apart with the source in the subarray field-of-view on the 4.5\,$\mu$m array.  The measurements were taken in staring mode (no repositoning within an AOR), and used PCRS Peak-Up to establish the position of XO-3b at the beginning of each AOR.\footnote{http://irachpp.spitzer.caltech.edu/page/Obs\%20Planning} Table \ref{xo3meas} gives the observation start time, {\sl Spitzer} AOR numbers, and the eclipse number \citep[for comparison with][Table 1]{2014ApJ...794..134W}.


