\label{edepth_sim_v_r_bias}}
\end{figure*}

\subsubsection{Reliability}
We define the {\it reliability}, $r$, to be the ratio between the intrinsic variability of a set of measurements to their observed variability, for a given method. In the context of eclipse depth measurements the intrinsic variability is the standard deviation in the depth due only to photon noise, $\sigma_{{\rm\scriptscriptstyle} phot}$ (Equation \ref{photon_noise}), and the observed variability is the measured standard deviation in the depth, ${\rm SD}$.  The measured variance contains both the photon noise and the variance due to ``measurement error,'' caused by residual correlated noise.  The value of $r \equiv \sigma_{{\rm\scriptscriptstyle} phot}/({\rm SD})$ is unitless and can range from 0 (all scatter due to measurement error) to 1 (no measurement error).  Reliability is essentially a normalized measure of precision, and is closely related to repeatability (see below).  

We list the computed values of $r$ for each method in column 9 of Tables \ref{eclipse_depth_stats} and \ref{eclipse_depth_stats_sim}.  For the real data, the reliability is quite high in most cases, with an average of ${\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu{r}\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu}=0.78$, suggesting that the bulk of the scatter is due to intrinsic photon noise.  The kernel regression (KR/Data and KR/Pmap) and ICA techniques appear to have very little correlated noise (standard deviations are consistent with photon noise).  For the simulated data, however, the values are lower, with an average reliability of ${\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu{r}\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu}=0.45$.  

Figures \ref{real_rep_rel} and \ref{fake_rep_rel} are scatterplots of repeatability vs. reliability for the real and simulated eclipse depths, respectively. The values appear inversely correlated, which is not surprising.  If two values are drawn from the same distribution, the variance in the difference between the values should be twice the variance of the original distribution, $[{\rm SD}(\Delta_{ij})]^2 = 2({\rm SD})^2$.  Thus by the definition of $r$, we expect $R = \sqrt{2}\sigma_{{\rm\scriptscriptstyle} phot}r^{-1}$.  We overlay this theoretical curve, as well as linear fits to $R$ as a function of $r^{-1}$ on Figures \ref{real_rep_rel} and \ref{fake_rep_rel}. The differences in the two curves for each plot are very slight, indicating statistical self-consistency between $[{\rm SD}(\Delta_{ij})]$ and SD.

Figure \ref{rel_real_fake} plots the reliability for simulated data as a function of that for real data, for the 7 decorrelation methods, with lines of different slope overlaid. There seems to be no relationship between the reliability measures for real and simulated eclipses, except that the simulated values are nearly all lower than their real counterparts.   Only BLISS has a similar reliability for both real and simulated data ($r=0.59$ and 0.63, respectively).   The kernel regression techniques both show the largest decrease, with $r_{{\rm\scriptscriptstyle} sim} \approx 0.4\,r_{{\rm\scriptscriptstyle} real}$. We conclude that BLISS is most robust to increases in positional dispersion, the main source of additional correlated noise between the simulated and real datasets.  The (gaussian) kernel regression methods seem to be least robust to such changes.\\


